### Description

When using Angular 19's new `@if` and `@else` syntax in a standalone component, IntelliJ IDEA flags the template with the error:
`Unterminated expansion form. If you have unescaped '{', use '{{ "{" }}' to escape it.`
Despite this, the code compiles and runs correctly in the browser. It seems the IDE does not fully recognize the syntax, causing it to misinterpret braces within the template.

### Minimal Reproduction

**Component:**
```ts[]
import { Component, Input, signal } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-task-details',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    @if(task(); as currentTask;) {
        <div class="task-details">
            <h2>Task Details</h2>
            <p><strong>Title:</strong> {{ currentTask.title }}</p>
            <p><strong>Status:</strong> {{ currentTask.completed ? 'Completed' : 'Pending' }}</p>
            <button (click)="clearSelection()">Clear Selection</button>
        </div>
    }
    @else {
        <ng-template #noTask>
            <p>Select a task to view its details.</p>
        </ng-template>
    }
  `,
  styles: [
    `
      .task-details {
        border: 1px solid #ddd;
        padding: 1rem;
        border-radius: 4px;
        background-color: #f9f9f9;
      }
    `,
  ],
})
export class TaskDetailsComponent {
  @Input() task = signal<any>(null);

  clearSelection() {
    this.task.set(null);
  }
}
```
**Dependancies:**
```json[]
{
  "@angular/animations": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/common": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/compiler": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/core": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/forms": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/platform-browser": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/platform-browser-dynamic": "^19.0.0",
  "@angular/router": "^19.0.0",
  "typescript": "~5.6.2"
}
```

### Steps to Reproduce:
1. Use the provided component code in an Angular 19 standalone project.
2. Open the project in IntelliJ IDEA.
3. Observe the error in the IDE.

### Expected Behavior:
The IDE should properly recognize and support Angular 19's new `@if` and `@else` syntax without throwing errors.

### Observed Behavior:
The IDE flags the syntax as an error, even though the code compiles and runs successfully in the browser.

### Workarounds:
- Use legacy directives like `*ngIf` until tooling fully supports the new syntax.
- Temporarily disable linting or inspections for affected code sections in the IDE.

### Exception or Error

```text
Unterminated expansion form. If you have unescaped '{', use '{{ "{" }}' to escape it.
```

### Your Environment

```text
IDE: IntelliJ IDEA

Angular CLI: 19.0.6
Node: 18.20.5
Package Manager: npm 10.8.2
OS: win32 x64

Angular: undefined
...

Package                      Version
------------------------------------------------------
@angular-devkit/architect    0.1900.6 (cli-only)
@angular-devkit/core         19.0.6 (cli-only)
@angular-devkit/schematics   19.0.6 (cli-only)
@schematics/angular          19.0.6 (cli-only)
```

### Anything else relevant?

This is likely due to incomplete support in IntelliJ IDEA(2023.01.03 (Ultimate Edition)) or the Angular Language Service. Feedback and improvements to the tooling would be greatly appreciated.

### Feature Description

I use a materialConfig to design my Material components uniformly across multiple apps. For certain Material components, I donâ€™t want to use the ripple effect. Currently, Iâ€™m achieving this for mat-input using CSS like this:
```scss
mat-form-field .mdc-line-ripple { 
  display: none; 
}
```
Since Iâ€™m not sure if this works for textarea, other appearances, etc., it would be nice to have a configuration to disable the ripple effect consistently:
```ts
import { MAT_FORM_FIELD_DEFAULT_OPTIONS, MatFormFieldDefaultOptions } from '@angular/material/form-field';

export const materialConfig = [
  {
    provide: MAT_FORM_FIELD_DEFAULT_OPTIONS,
    useValue: {
      ripple: false, // For example, like this.
      floatLabel: 'always',
    } as MatFormFieldDefaultOptions,
  },
];
```
Alternatively, this could be handled via a CSS variable, but I would prefer a DefaultOption.
